	<tr><td background="/lotr/gfx/mom/whi_07.gif"></td>
		<td bgcolor="#FFFFFF" background="/lotr/gfx/mom/whi_08.gif"><font class="bfont"><font class="h1font"> LOTR Q&A Rulings from 11/13/03<br></font><br><font class="h2font"> <b>Overall Rating:</b> </font><img src="/lotr/gfx/star2.gif" width="19" height="21" border="0" align="absmiddle"><img src="/lotr/gfx/star2.gif" width="19" height="21" border="0" align="absmiddle"><img src="/lotr/gfx/star2.gif" width="19" height="21" border="0" align="absmiddle"><img src="/lotr/gfx/star2.gif" width="19" height="21" border="0" align="absmiddle"><img src="/lotr/gfx/star2.gif" width="19" height="21" border="0" align="absmiddle"><font size='1'>(4.75)</font><br><font class="h2font"> <b>Author:</b> <A HREF='http://www.decktech.net/lotr/main/mpage.php?member=617'>Enrique "Max of Tat" Huerta</A></font><font class="afont"> <a href='http://www.decktech.net/lotr/main/mpage.php?member=617&sub=1'> (Subscribe to this member)</a><br><font class="h2font"> <b>Date Submitted:</b> November 27, 2003</font><p align='justify'><font class="bfont"> Not for review<br />
Originally posted 11/13/03<br />
==========================<br />
Hello All!!<br />
<br />
   Well, it looks like I&#39;m back on schedule. At first it looked like it was going to be a light update, but as I started answering the question, I realized that this update was still very informative. (=<br />
<br />
   Return of the King released last week, and is now tournament legal. Lots of new and exciting cards. Not to mention 2 new game mechanics, initiative and threats. Time will tell on all of that. But until then, have fun and if you have any questions, I&#39;m always here. (=<br />
<br />
   Lastly, don&#39;t forget to take a look at the Star Trek 2E contest I&#39;m sponsoring. A complete box of Call to Arms goes to the winner, so don&#39;t miss out!!<br />
<br />
- Enrique<br />
<br />
<br />
<h3>Questions about Card Rulings:</h3><br />
<b>Hey Enrique, If a companion dies DURING a skirmish (is wounded to death by Red Wrath, for example) and his/her death sets off a bunch of threats, can Eowyn, Sister-Daughter of Theoden just take them all and discard cards to prevent most of the wounds? I guess the same question could be asked for men bearing Armor or King&#39;s Mail? [Patrick Sullivan]</b><br />
<br />
When a character dies as a result of a skirmish (either a skirmish action or by losing the skirmish) the skirmish is still not over until all responses to winning or losing the skirmish have resolve. This includes the placing the theats on companions. As such you may use the Ruling Ring and Eowyn, sister-daughter of Theoden&#39;s game text.<br />
<br />
Each wound is placed one at a time, so for each wound you would have to discard 2 cards to prevent it. If 3 threats needed to be placed, you could assign each on to her, and as soon as she became exhausted she would be able to prevent the subcequent wounds with game text.<br />
<br />
However this is not the same as a companion with Armor or King&#39;s Mail. Armor and King&#39;s Mail do not prevent wounds, they limit them. If Eowyn was bearing Armor, she would still have to discard cards for each wound, since because she&#39;s preventing the wound, she hasn&#39;t received her 1 wound limit. If she were to take 1 wound (assuming she had 2 vitality) you would then not be allowed to assign any more wounds to her during this skirmish phase because of the Armor&#39;s 1 wound limit. If a character cannot take wound (or further wounds), you cannot assign any to them either. Those wounds would have to be assigned elsewhere. <br />
<br />
<b>Ok, let&#39;s say there&#39;s an Easterling with a Polearm fighting against my Frodo with one burden. The Easterling is exhausted. If I play Power According to His Stature, does the Easterling take a wound, or is the second burden added first, immediately activating the Polearm&#39;s anti-wound text? [Jason]</b><br />
<br />
You always pay the costs of an action before you can get any of the effects of the action. As soon as the Free People&#39;s Player adds another burden (to pay the cost of Power According to His Stature) the game text of the Easterling Polearm is triggered. Because of the Polearms gametext, the Easterling would not receive any wounds.<br />
<br />
<b>G&#39;day! long time listener, first time caller... erm.. emailer... <br />
<br />
Ok the old &quot;For Each&quot; rears its head frequently in our local area. Witch king, lord of angmar, +2 for each nagzul he can spot. those other nazgul die, what happens? same with ancient chieftain. I&#39;ve looked and looked and can&#39;t find an answer! help! :) [Machine]</b><br />
<br />
The strength of characters, such at the Witch-King, Ancient Chieftain, Morgul Hunter, and Denethor, constant check and re-check to determine their current strength. Every time a Nazgul dies, the Witch-king, Lord of Angmar loses a +2 bonus. Depending on the order and outcome of the skirmishes, the Witch-king&#39;s strength can vary greatly.  <br />
<br />
<b>Hi Enrique. <br />
I was wondering about Saruman, Servant of the Eye. <br />
His gametext says: <br />
&quot;Assignment: Exert Saruman to assign an (Isengard) Minion to a companion (except the ring-bearer). That companion may exert to prevent this.&quot; <br />
<br />
I was wondering if you could use Saruman to assign multiple minions to one companion in hopes of an overwhelm, or would that companion need a defender bonus to do that? <br />
<br />
Thanks in advance! :) [Underhill]</b><br />
<br />
Saruman, Servant of the Eye is an assignment action. ALL assignment actions must involve previously unassigned characters and can only result in one-on-one skirmishes. The only 2 exceptions, are when the Free Peoples Player assigns minions to a Defender +X and when the Shadow player assigns left over minions. You can not use Saruman to assign more than one minion to the same character, even if that character is a Defender +X.<br />
<br />
<h3>Questions about Game/Tournament Rulings:</h3><br />
<br />
<b>Hi Enrique,<br />
have a ques: Imagine Frodo receives three wounds dealt by Lurtz with Sword. May I put on the ring after the first or the second wound to split the damage up into wounds and burdens or do I have to take all wounds simultaniously?<br />
<br />
Guess I&#39;ve got Gilmi, Dwarf of the Mountain race on table and play skilled defender. I heal one wound on him, but may I also choose, which card text I use - which card remains on the table?<br />
<br />
Could you maybe give me a hint how to survive hate? Is playing maneuver events my only chance or is THE hate-beating card out there and I haven&#39;t found it?<br />
<br />
When using Grima-Wormtongue, the ring does count when it&#39;s up to Grima to spot three cards, right? Thx a lot [Dirayn]</b><br />
<br />
1. Note that the 4 Rings each operate differently. In this situation, the Ruling Ring and Isildur&#39;s Bane work pretty much the same way. So you may take the first wound on Frodo, and as you&#39;re &quot;about to take the second wound&quot; you may respond with The One Ring to take burdens instead of the second wound. Because the One Ring is already on, you&#39;ll have no choice about the third wound, as it will have to be converted to burdens. You can of course choose to wait until the third wound, before you decide to put on the One Ring.<br />
<br />
For The Answer to All Riddles, you&#39;ll have to use the Skirmish action to first put on the One Ring (before you resolve the skirmish). If the Answer to All Riddles is on, all 3 of the wounds will become burdens. You would not get a choice.<br />
<br />
For the new Such a Weight to Carry, you have to put the One Ring on during the maneuver phase. And like the Answer to All Riddles, once it&#39;s on, all wounds would be converted to burdens. You would have no choice.<br />
<br />
2. Lord of the Rings does not allow you to switch versions of a persona in the middle of the game. If you first played Gimli, Dwarf of the Mountain Race, that is the version of Gimli that would have to remain in play. Note: that if Gimli was to leave play (other then going to the Dead Pile), you would be free to play any version of him as you wish. You&#39;re also allowed to play a different version (assuming you have one already in your deck) from game to game.<br />
<br />
3. No hints neccessary. (= In my opinion, the best form of Hate protection is Eowyn, Lady of Rohan. Her ability to prevent wounds to unbound companions can be the difference between losing a vital character and surviving an Orc swarm. She however is not the only form of protection:<br />
 - Dauntless Hunter and a couple of unbound hobbits can make Hate too expensive to used effectively.<br />
 - Some Who Resisted can have a similar effect.<br />
 - Skinbark, Fladrif has a special ability similar to Eowyn, except he only protects unbound hobbits.<br />
 - Orc Bane, Quick As May Be, Barak-kazad, Defend It and Hope, etc... allow you to wound or exert the minion before they are able to do it to you.<br />
<br />
It all really depends on your decktype of choice. If you think you can fit any of these cards in your deck, they should be able to help you a  little.<br />
<br />
4. Two things to remember. The One Ring is not a Free Peoples card nor a Shadow card. It is it&#39;s own card type, and is not like any other type. Grima, Wormtonque only puts Free Peoples cards back into the player&#39;s hand. Since the One Ring is not a Free Peoples card, it would not go back to hand.<br />
<br />
Secondly, Grima only works against unbound companions. Frodo (and Sam) are always Ring-bound and therefore can never be affected by Grima. Since Frodo and Sam are currently the only Ring-bearers in the game, you should have very few occassions in which you have to worry about this situation. (=<br />
<br />
<b>Hi Enrique,<br />
<br />
I&#39;ve got one of this &quot;must sound stupid&quot;-questions for you: At the beginning of the game, when players choose the amount of burdens to start with, are they aware of their starting hand or do they draw their first cards afterwards?<br />
In the online version of the game is a common thing to first bid and then starting your fellowship phase with quite a couple of shadow cards. In my opinion the exact procedure isn&#39;t in the rulebooks. [Diraya]</b><br />
<br />
There is a proper procedure for the start of the game. In fact, it was probably the most frequently asked question at the World Cup a few weeks ago. (So, as you see, even the best in the world ask these questions too.)<br />
<br />
<b>#1 Bid.</b> Many players do not realize that this is the first step. Most assume that you sit down show your Frodo first. The reason that this isn&#39;t first is because of multiplayer. In multiplayer, you can not determine when you&#39;re going to sit until after the bids are done.<br />
<br />
<b>#2 Sit down, show your Frodo, your One Ring and place your burdens.</b> The logical next step.<br />
<br />
<b>#3 The player that goes first, plays their Site 1 and everyone places their move token on the site.</b><br />
<br />
<b>#4 In order of turn, each player plays their starting fellowship from their draw deck.</b> Technically speaking, the starting fellowship is part of your draw deck. Most people start with the same fellowship every game, but you do not have to. You may switch it out with any legal starting fellowship in your draw deck. It is also important to remember to play your starting fellowship in a correct order. If you plan on starting with Quickbeam, Pippin and Merry, then you need to play the unbound hobbits before Quickbeam, or you&#39;ll have played too much twilight for your starting fellowship. The same is true with Eomer and (new) Theoden that play for -1 if you can spot a [Rohan] Man first.<br />
<br />
<b>#5 Start the game and draw 8 cards. (=</b><br />
<br />
- Enrique<br />
